The best way to understand why tribalism is the mover and shaper of society is to consider who you trust more: a family member, or a stranger? It might be easy for you to rebut that with an appeal to individualism in this day and age, but put yourself in the shoes of your ancestors, for whom choosing who to associate with and trust was often a matter of life and death. If he made the decision to trust the outsider, there was a greater chance that it would end up hurting him compared to if he had trusted a family member. Because of their genetic relationship to each other, the family member, or a member of a close-knit community have a vested interest in helping each other (natural selection), which is absent in members of the outgroup, who are undoubtedly more concerned with their own genetic interest.

There are other factors that can divide groups, like ideology or religion, but in a multiracial society, race will be the deciding factor that rises to prominence in all decisions of who to associate with. America is an example of this.

I'll reply to your next point separately just to keep from archiving.

>>252177676
>I don't love my family because of a genetic relationship
This is going to be hyperbolic, but it still makes my point: if you were raised by wolves or gorillas, would you love them in the same way that you love your birth family? You'd probably experience the same feelings of familiarity and would have regular interaction, but at the end of the day, you are human, and they are animals. Whatever relationship you share with those gorillas cannot be equated to the relationship you'd otherwise have with your birth family. My point is that the genetic similarities you share with your kin are the basis for that familial love.

As I mentioned earlier though, I do acknowledge that race is not everything in these matters, so you could instead think of it like: would you get along with a group of friends who love blaring really loud music and getting into trouble (assuming that you hate these things) or are you going to get along better with a group of friends who share your interests? How much you want to factor genetic circumstances into these personality traits is up to you, but if you knew that a particular group is more likely to act in a way that you find intolerable, will you generally be willing to associate with them? Keyword being generally, mind you.
